04936nam a22007455i 9780520917453DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209174537 a10.1525/97805209174532doi  a(DE-B1597)542420  a(OCoLC)1149533152  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHG1282b.V66 1996eb 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a332.4/9512201 avon Glahn, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFountain of Fortune :bMoney and Monetary Policy in China, 1000-1700 /cRichard von Glahn.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b1 frontisp., 12 figures, 2 maps, 23 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. The Fundamentals of Classical Chinese Monetary Analysis -- t2. Transition to the Silver Economy, 1000-1435 -- t3. Coinage in the Dawning Age of Silver, 1435-1570 -- t4. Foreign Silver and China’s “Silver Century,” 1550-1650 -- t5. Coin vs. Silver -- t6. The Great Debasements -- t7. The “Monetary Crisis” of the Seventeenth Century -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe most striking feature of Wutong, the preeminent God of Wealth in late imperial China, was the deity’s diabolical character. Wutong was perceived not as a heroic figure or paragon but rather as an embodiment of greed and lust, a maleficent demon who preyed on the weak and vulnerable. In The Sinister Way, Richard von Glahn examines the emergence and evolution of the Wutong cult within the larger framework of the historical development of Chinese popular or vernacular religion—as opposed to institutional religions such as Buddhism or Daoism. Von Glahn’s study, spanning three millennia, gives due recognition to the morally ambivalent and demonic aspects of divine power within the common Chinese religious culture.Surveying Chinese religion from 1000 BCE to the beginning of the twentieth century, The Sinister Way views the Wutong cult as by no means an aberration. In Von Glahn’s work we see how, from earliest times, the Chinese imagined an enchanted world populated by fiendish fairies and goblins, ancient stones and trees that spring suddenly to life, ghosts of the unshriven dead, and the blood-eating spirits of the mountains and forests. From earliest times, too, we find in Chinese religious culture an abiding tension between two fundamental orientations: on one hand, belief in the power of sacrifice and exorcism to win blessings and avert calamity through direct appeal to a multitude of gods; on the other, faith in an all-encompassing moral equilibrium inhering in the cosmos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonetary policy ChinaxHistory. 0aMonetary policyxHistoryxChinaxChina. 0aMonetary policyzChinaxHistory. 0aMoneyxHistoryxChina. 0aMoneyzChinaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  achinese monetary history.  aclassic.  acommon chinese religious culture.  adeitys diabolical character.  adivine power.  aembodiment of greed and lust.  aemergence and evolution of wutong cult.  afascinating.  ahistorical development of chinese popular religions.  alate imperial china.  amaleficent demon.  apreeminent god of wealth.  apreyed on weak and vulnerable.  awutong cult.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020408940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520917453?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917453423Cover